Rating: 3
We thought this soup was great--reminded me of my Grandma's soup. We didn't have bacon or fresh corn, so substituted diced prosciutto and frozen white corn, added celery and, as my Grandma would have done, 2 chopped hard boiled eggs at the end. We poached the chicken breasts in the broth and then cut them up.

Rating: 2
What this recipe might lack in pizazz, it makes up for in speed and efficiency. You can whip it up quick like a bunny! As a previous reviewer noted, puree-ing some of the potatoes/corn makes the soup creamier, without adding more fat (I drain most of the drippings from the bacon).

Rating: 2
I love corn chowder, so I went all-out making this soup: homemade chicken stock, fresh corn off the cob, artisanal slab bacon, etc. It ended up somewhat underwhelming: the brown coloring from cooking the bacon gave the soup a not-so-pretty dark color, there really wasn't as much corn flavor as I would have liked, and I had to pepper the soup so much to get flavor out of it that my wrist still hurts from grinding! It tasted a little better the second day after the flavors had time to blend and concentrate, but even then the high point of the soup was the chunks of yummy bacon I tossed on top of each serving. I guess I'll keep on searching for the perfect corn chowder recipe.

Rating: 2
This soup was pretty good after some much-needed doctoring. The recipe is rather bland on its own. I added more thyme, several dashes of tabasco and lots of black pepper. The flavor would definitely mature into something more special if you prepared the soup a day ahead of time... which is what I'll do when I make it again.

Rating: 4
This has become one of our family's favorite comfort foods. I use evaporated low fat milk instead of the cream and no body complained, browned the chicken along with the onions for a richer flavor and color, and thickened slightly with a little flour and water since we prefer a chowder that is a little thicker. I also use more thyme than called for. Absolutley a keeper!!

Rating: 3
I'm surprised by the negative reviews. I've made this a couple of times and my family has thoroughly enjoyed. I replace the cream with evaporated milk to save the calories, and am very generous with the fresh thyme. It definately falls into the comfort food category, but is that a bad thing?

Rating: 2
This was certainly simple enough to make. I used fresh corn off the cob, chicken breast meat, and a combination of fresh thyme and marjoram, less than what was called for. We thought the chowder was too thin, so I pureed some of the potato and corn, then added it back to the pot. Because I used fresh-picked corn, it came out very sweet, too sweet for my taste. Also, after sitting overnight, the flavor of the herbs became really strong. I didn't love this chowder, didn't hate it. I'm not ready to discard the recipe, but I definitely will tweak it somehow to make it better. I'll look for comments from other cooks before I try it next time.

